  "prompt": "What's the difference between voltage, current, and watts?",
  "response": "Here's a simple explanation of voltage, current, and watts:\n\nVoltage (V):\n- Electrical \"pressure\" or potential difference\n- Measures the force pushing electrons through a circuit\n- Like water pressure in a pipe\n- Measured in volts\n\nCurrent (I):\n- Flow of electrons through a circuit\n- Amount of electrical charge moving past a point\n- Like the amount of water flowing through a pipe\n- Measured in amperes (amps)\n\nWatts (W):\n- Measure of electrical power\n- Calculated by multiplying voltage and current\n- Represents the rate of energy consumption or production\n- Formula: Watts = Volts \u00d7 Amps\n- Indicates how much energy is being used or generated\n\nAnalogy:\n- Voltage = Water pressure\n- Current = Water flow rate\n- Watts = Total water power/energy\n\nExample:\n- A 60-watt light bulb at 120 volts uses 0.5 amps (60W \u00f7 120V = 0.5A)\n\nEach measurement describes a different aspect of electricity, working together to explain electrical systems.",
